(in-package :cl-user)

; rename-on-conflict generates a new filename by appending a counter to the original name if it conflicts with existing files.
; 
; Parameters:
;   existing-files - a list of strings representing existing filenames
;   new-file - a string representing the desired new filename
;
; Returns:
;   A string representing the new filename, either the original if no conflict exists,
;   or the original with a counter appended if conflicts are found.
(defun rename-on-conflict (existing-files new-file)
  (if (not (member new-file existing-files :test #'string=))
      new-file
      (let ((counter 1))
        (loop while (member (format nil "~a~d" new-file counter) existing-files :test #'string=)
              do (incf counter))
        (format nil "~a~d" new-file counter))))

(in-package :cl-user)

; count-unique-vowels returns the count of unique vowels in the given string.
; Vowels are considered case insensitively (both uppercase and lowercase are treated the same).
; The function checks each character in the string, converts it to lowercase,
; and checks if it's one of the vowels 'a', 'e', 'i', 'o', or 'u'.
; It then counts how many unique vowels were found.
(defun count-unique-vowels (s)
  (let ((vowels '(#\a #\e #\i #\o #\u))
        (unique-vowels (make-hash-table :test 'equal)))
    (loop for char across s
          for lower-char = (char-downcase char)
          when (member lower-char vowels :test #'char=)
          do (setf (gethash lower-char unique-vowels) t))
    (hash-table-count unique-vowels)))

(defpackage :subarray-utils
  (:use :cl)
  (:export :num-special-subarrays))

(in-package :subarray-utils)

(defun num-special-subarrays (arr k)
  "Calculates the number of special subarrays where the product of all elements is less than k.
Uses a sliding window approach for efficient computation."
  (if (<= k 1)
      0
      (let ((product 1)
            (result 0)
            (left 0))
        (loop for right from 0 below (length arr)
              for value = (nth right arr)
              do (setf product (* product value))
              (loop while (>= product k)
                    do (setf product (/ product (nth left arr)))
                    (incf left))
              (incf result (- right left -1)))
        result)))

(defpackage :kth-occurrence
  (:use :cl)
  (:export :find-kth-occurrence :process-test-cases))

(in-package :kth-occurrence)

(defun find-kth-occurrence (n arr x k)
  (let ((count 0)
        (position -1))
    (dotimes (idx n position)
      (when (= (nth idx arr) x)
        (incf count)
        (when (= count k)
          (setf position (1+ idx))
          (return position))))))

(defun process-test-cases (t-cases test-cases)
  (let ((results '()))
    (dotimes (i t-cases (reverse results))
      (let* ((case (nth i test-cases))
             (n (first case))
             (arr (second case))
             (x (third case))
             (k (fourth case)))
        (push (find-kth-occurrence n arr x k) results)))))

(in-package :cl-user)

; count-swaps-to-sort calculates the minimum number of indices where elements need to be swapped
; to make the list sorted in non-decreasing order.
; It does this by comparing the original list with a sorted version of the list and counting
; the positions where the elements differ.
(defun count-swaps-to-sort (heights)
  (let ((sorted-heights (sort (copy-list heights) #'<))
        (out-of-place-count 0))
    (dotimes (i (length heights) out-of-place-count)
      (when (not (equal (nth i heights) (nth i sorted-heights)))
        (incf out-of-place-count)))))

(in-package :cl-user)

;;; find-min-abs-difference-split calculates the optimal split point in an array
;;; that minimizes the absolute difference between the sums of the two parts.
;;; It takes a list of test cases, where each test case is a cons of (n . array),
;;; and returns a list of optimal split positions (1-based index).
(defun find-min-abs-difference-split (test-cases)
  (mapcar 
   (lambda (test-case)
     (let* ((n (car test-case))
            (array (cdr test-case))
            (total-sum (apply #'+ array))
            (min-diff most-positive-fixnum)
            (sum-A 0)
            best-k)
       (dotimes (k (1- n) best-k)
         (incf sum-A (nth k array))
         (let* ((sum-B (- total-sum sum-A))
                (diff (abs (- sum-A sum-B))))
           (when (< diff min-diff)
             (setf min-diff diff
                   best-k (1+ k)))))))  ; Using 1-based index as in Python
   test-cases))

Results:
  Test case 1: optimal split at position 2
  Test case 2: optimal split at position 3
  Test case 3: optimal split at position 2
  Test case 4: optimal split at position 1

                      (5 . (1 2 3 4 5))
                      (3 . (10 20 30))
                      (2 . (5 5)))))
    (let ((results (cl-user::find-min-abs-difference-split test-cases)))
      (assert (= (nth 0 results) 2) () "Test case 1 failed")
      (assert (= (nth 1 results) 3) () "Test case 2 failed")
      (assert (= (nth 2 results) 2) () "Test case 3 failed")
      (assert (= (nth 3 results) 1) () "Test case 4 failed")
      (format t "All tests passed!~%"))))

(run-tests)

; find-maximum-total-distance calculates the total distance covered by all animals
; based on their segments and velocities.
; Parameters:
; - n: number of animals (unused in the calculation, but kept for interface consistency)
; - k: number of segments
; - segment-lengths: list of lengths for each segment
; - animals: list of animal data, where each animal is represented as (start-segment end-segment velocity)
; Returns the sum of the total distance covered by all animals across all segments.
(defun find-maximum-total-distance (n k segment-lengths animals)
  (let ((distance-covered (make-list k :initial-element 0)))
    (dolist (animal animals)
      (destructuring-bind (si ei vi) animal
        (loop for segment from (1- si) below ei
              do (incf (nth segment distance-covered)
                       (* (nth segment segment-lengths) vi)))))
    (apply #'+ distance-covered)))

(defpackage :ab-substring
  (:use :cl)
  (:export :longest-ab-substring))

(in-package :ab-substring)

(defun longest-ab-substring (s)
  (let ((balance-map (make-hash-table))
        (balance 0)
        (max-len 0)
        (start-idx -1))
    (setf (gethash 0 balance-map) -1)
    (loop for idx from 0 below (length s)
          for char = (char s idx)
          do (cond ((char= char #\A) (incf balance))
                   ((char= char #\B) (decf balance)))
          do (if (gethash balance balance-map)
                 (let ((prev-idx (gethash balance balance-map)))
                   (when (> (- idx prev-idx) max-len)
                     (setf max-len (- idx prev-idx)
                           start-idx (1+ prev-idx))))
                 (setf (gethash balance balance-map) idx)))
    (if (> max-len 0)
        (subseq s start-idx (+ start-idx max-len))
        "")))

(defpackage :string-utils
  (:use :cl)
  (:export :closest-string :string-similarity))

(in-package :string-utils)

(defun closest-string (strings target)
  (let ((closest nil)
        (min-distance most-positive-double-float))
    (dolist (string strings closest)
      (let* ((distance (string-similarity string target))
             (actual-distance (- 1.0 distance)))
        (when (< actual-distance min-distance)
          (setf min-distance actual-distance
                closest string))))))

(defun string-similarity (str1 str2)
  (let ((len1 (length str1))
        (len2 (length str2)))
    (if (or (zerop len1) (zerop len2))
        0.0
        (let ((max-length (max len1 len2))
              (matches 0))
          (dotimes (i (min len1 len2) (/ (float matches) max-length))
            (when (char= (char str1 i) (char str2 i))
              (incf matches)))))))

(in-package :cl-user)

;; partition-count calculates the number of ways to partition the integer n into non-negative integers.
;; It uses dynamic programming to build a solution iteratively.
;; The function initializes a 2D array (dp) where dp[i][j] represents the number of ways to partition j using integers up to i.
;; The base case is that there's exactly one way to partition 0 (the empty partition).
;; For each integer i from 1 to n, and for each j from 1 to n, the function updates dp[i][j] based on whether j >= i.
;; If j >= i, dp[i][j] is the sum of dp[i-1][j] (exclude i) and dp[i][j-i] (include i).
;; Otherwise, dp[i][j] is simply dp[i-1][j].
(defun partition-count (n)
  (let ((dp (make-array (list (1+ n) (1+ n)) :initial-element 0)))
    ;; Base case: one way to partition 0
    (dotimes (i (1+ n))
      (setf (aref dp i 0) 1))
    ;; Populate the dp table
    (dotimes (i (1+ n))
      (dotimes (j (1+ n))
        (when (and (>= i 1) (>= j 1))
          (if (>= j i)
              (setf (aref dp i j) (+ (aref dp (1- i) j) (aref dp i (- j i))))
              (setf (aref dp i j) (aref dp (1- i) j))))))
    (aref dp n n)))

(in-package :cl-user)

;; pivot-index finds the pivot index in a list of numbers where the sum of elements 
;; to the left is equal to the sum of elements to the right.
;; If no such index exists, it returns -1.
;; The function first calculates the total sum of the list, then iterates through 
;; the list while maintaining a running sum of the left elements.
;; For each element, it checks if the left sum equals the total sum minus the 
;; left sum and the current element.
(defun pivot-index (nums)
  (let ((total-sum (apply #'+ nums))
        (left-sum 0))

; min-changes-to-sort-heights calculates the minimum number of changes required
; to make a list of heights non-decreasing. It does this by finding the length
; of the longest common subsequence (LCS) between the original list and its sorted
; version, then subtracting this from the total length of the list.
(defun min-changes-to-sort-heights (heights)
  (let* ((n (length heights))
         (sorted-heights (sort (copy-list heights) #'<))
         (dp (make-array (list (1+ n) (1+ n)) :initial-element 0)))
    (if (zerop n)
        0
        (progn
          (dotimes (i n)
            (dotimes (j n)
              (if (equal (nth i heights) (nth j sorted-heights))
                  (setf (aref dp (1+ i) (1+ j)) (1+ (aref dp i j)))
                  (setf (aref dp (1+ i) (1+ j)) 
                        (max (aref dp (1+ i) j) (aref dp i (1+ j)))))))
          (- n (aref dp n n))))))

(in-package :cl-user)

; rotate-wheel calculates the final configuration of an encoder wheel after applying a series of rotation operations.
; The wheel is rotated by the net rotation (sum of all operations modulo n), and the result is constructed by
; concatenating the last 'net-rotation' elements with the rest of the wheel.
; Parameters:
;   n - number of positions on the wheel (integer)
;   wheel - initial configuration of the wheel (list of integers)
;   operations - list of rotation operations (list of integers)
; Returns:
;   The final configuration of the wheel (list of integers)
(defun rotate-wheel (n wheel operations)
  (let* ((net-rotation (mod (apply #'+ operations) n))
         (net-rotation (if (minusp net-rotation) (+ net-rotation n) net-rotation)))
    (append (subseq wheel (- (length wheel) net-rotation))
            (subseq wheel 0 (- (length wheel) net-rotation)))))

; process-test-cases processes multiple test cases by applying rotate-wheel to each one.
; Parameters:
;   test-cases - a list of test cases, where each test case is a list of (n wheel operations)
; Returns:
;   A list of final wheel configurations for each test case (list of lists of integers)
(defun process-test-cases (test-cases)
  (mapcar (lambda (test-case)
            (destructuring-bind (n wheel operations) test-case
              (rotate-wheel n wheel operations)))
          test-cases))

(in-package :cl-user)

; min-steps calculates the minimum number of steps required to reach the bottom-right corner
; of the maze from the top-left corner. The maze is represented as a list of lists where
; '0' represents a passable cell and '1' represents a blocked cell.
; If the destination is unreachable, it returns -1.
(defun min-steps (maze)
  (if (or (null maze) (null (first maze)) 
          (char= (aref (first maze) 0) #\1) 
          (char= (aref (first (last maze)) (1- (length (first maze)))) #\1))
      -1
      (let* ((rows (length maze))
             (cols (length (first maze)))
             (directions '((1 0) (-1 0) (0 1) (0 -1))) ; Down, Up, Right, Left
             (queue (list (list 0 0 0))) ; (row col steps)
             (visited (make-hash-table :test 'equal)))
        (setf (gethash '(0 0) visited) t)
        (loop while queue do
          (let* ((current (pop queue))
                 (row (first current))
                 (col (second current))
                 (steps (third current)))
            (when (and (= row (1- rows)) (= col (1- cols)))
              (return-from min-steps steps))
            (dolist (dir directions)
              (let* ((dr (first dir))
                     (dc (second dir))
                     (r (+ row dr))
                     (c (+ col dc)))
                (when (and (>= r 0) (< r rows) (>= c 0) (< c cols)
                           (char= (aref (nth r maze) c) #\0)
                           (not (gethash (list r c) visited)))
                  (setf (gethash (list r c) visited) t)
                  (setq queue (append queue (list (list r c (1+ steps))))))))))
        -1)))

; find-adjacent-pair checks if there exists a pair of adjacent elements in a list of numbers
; that add up to the given target value. 
; It iterates through the list, checking each adjacent pair.
; Returns T if such a pair is found, otherwise NIL.
(defun find-adjacent-pair (numbers target)
  (loop for i from 0 below (1- (length numbers))
        when (= (+ (nth i numbers) (nth (1+ i) numbers)) target)
          do (return-from find-adjacent-pair t))
  nil)

(in-package :cl-user)

;;; Password Complexity Checker in Common Lisp

;;; check-password-complexity evaluates the complexity of a given password.
;;; It checks the length, presence of letters, digits, and special characters.
;;; Returns "Weak", "Moderate", or "Strong" based on the criteria.
(defun check-password-complexity (password)
  (let ((length-ok (>= (length password) 8))
        (has-letter (some #'alpha-char-p password))
        (has-digit (some #'digit-char-p password))
        (has-special (some (lambda (c) (find c "!\"#$%&'()*+,-./:;<=>?@[\\]^_`{|}~")) password)))
    (cond
      ((not length-ok) "Weak")
      ((and has-letter has-digit has-special) "Strong")
      ((and has-letter has-digit) "Moderate")
      (t "Weak"))))

;;; suggest-password-improvements provides suggestions to improve password complexity.
;;; Returns a list of suggestions based on what the password lacks.
(defun suggest-password-improvements (password)
  (let ((suggestions nil))
    (when (< (length password) 8)
      (push "Use at least 8 characters" suggestions))
    (unless (some #'digit-char-p password)
      (push "Include digits" suggestions))
    (unless (some #'alpha-char-p password)
      (push "Include letters" suggestions))
    (unless (some (lambda (c) (find c "!\"#$%&'()*+,-./:;<=>?@[\\]^_`{|}~")) password)
      (push "Include special characters" suggestions))
    (nreverse suggestions)))

(defpackage :password-test
  (:use :cl)
  (:export :run-tests))

(in-package :password-test)

(defun check-password-complexity (password)
  (let ((length-ok (>= (length password) 8))
        (has-letter (some #'alpha-char-p password))
        (has-digit (some #'digit-char-p password))
        (has-special (some (lambda (c) (find c "!\"#$%&'()*+,-./:;<=>?@[\\]^_`{|}~")) password)))
    (cond
      ((not length-ok) "Weak")
      ((and has-letter has-digit has-special) "Strong")
      ((and has-letter has-digit) "Moderate")
      (t "Weak"))))

;;; suggest-password-improvements provides suggestions to improve password complexity.
;;; Returns a list of suggestions based on what the password lacks.
(defun suggest-password-improvements (password)
  (let ((suggestions nil))
    (when (< (length password) 8)
      (push "Use at least 8 characters" suggestions))
    (unless (some #'digit-char-p password)
      (push "Include digits" suggestions))
    (unless (some #'alpha-char-p password)
      (push "Include letters" suggestions))
    (unless (some (lambda (c) (find c "!\"#$%&'()*+,-./:;<=>?@[\\]^_`{|}~")) password)
      (push "Include special characters" suggestions))
    (nreverse suggestions)))


(defun run-tests ()
  ;; Test check-password-complexity

;; min-moves-to-equal-candies calculates the minimum number of moves to make all elements of the list equal.
;; Each move consists of giving one candy from one child to another.
;; The function first sorts the list to find the median value, then calculates the sum of absolute differences
;; between each element and the median.
(defun min-moves-to-equal-candies (candies)
  (let* ((sorted-candies (sort (copy-list candies) #'<))
         (n (length sorted-candies))
         (median (nth (floor n 2) sorted-candies)))
    (reduce #'+ (mapcar (lambda (x) (abs (- x median))) sorted-candies))))

(in-package :cl-user)

;;; Binary Heap implementation in Common Lisp
;;; This module provides functions to create and manipulate a binary heap,
;;; including insertion, removal of the minimum element, and removal of the k smallest elements.

(defun heap-insert (heap key)
  (let ((new-heap (cons key heap)))
    (heapify-up new-heap (1- (length new-heap)))))

(defun heapify-up (heap index)
  (if (zerop index)
      heap
      (let ((parent-index (floor (1- index) 2)))
        (if (< (nth index heap) (nth parent-index heap))
            (heapify-up (swap heap index parent-index) parent-index)
            heap))))

(defun heap-remove-min (heap)
  (if (null heap)
      (values nil nil)
      (let ((min (first heap))
            (new-heap (append (last heap) (cdr heap))))
        (values min (heapify-down new-heap 0)))))

(defun heapify-down (heap index)
  (let* ((left-child (+ (* 2 index) 1))
         (right-child (+ (* 2 index) 2))
         (smallest index)
         (heap-size (length heap)))
    (when (and (< left-child heap-size)
               (< (nth left-child heap) (nth smallest heap)))
      (setf smallest left-child))
    (when (and (< right-child heap-size)
               (< (nth right-child heap) (nth smallest heap)))
      (setf smallest right-child))
    (if (/= smallest index)
        (heapify-down (swap heap index smallest) smallest)
        heap)))

(defun swap (heap i j)
  (let ((new-heap (copy-list heap)))
    (rotatef (nth i new-heap) (nth j new-heap))
    new-heap))

(defun heap-remove-k-min (heap k)
  (let ((result '())
        (current-heap heap))
    (dotimes (i k (values (reverse result) current-heap))
      (multiple-value-bind (min new-heap) (heap-remove-min current-heap)
        (push min result)
        (setf current-heap new-heap)))))

(in-package :cl-user)

;; multiply-scalar-to-columns-for-years multiplies a given scalar value to specific columns in a dataset
;; for a given list of years. The dataset is represented as a list of lists, where each sublist is a row.
;; The first row is assumed to be the header (column names), and the first column is assumed to be the year.
;;
;; Parameters:
;; data: The input dataset as a list of lists.
;; years: A list of years (as integers) to be modified.
;; columns: A list of column names (as strings) to be modified.
;; scalar: The scalar value (as a number) to multiply with.
;;
;; Returns:
;; The modified dataset as a list of lists.
(defun multiply-scalar-to-columns-for-years (data years columns scalar)
  (let* ((header (first data))
         (rows (rest data))
         (valid-columns (intersection columns header :test #'string=))
         (column-indices (mapcar (lambda (col) (position col header :test #'string=)) valid-columns))
         (modified-rows 
           (mapcar 
             (lambda (row) 
               (let ((year (first row)))
                 (if (member year years)
                     (append 
                       (list year)
                       (mapcar 
                         (lambda (idx val) 
                           (if (member idx column-indices)
                               (* val scalar)
                               val))
                         (iota (length (rest row)) :start 0)
                         (rest row)))
                     row)))
             rows)))
    (cons header modified-rows)))

;; Helper function to create a range of numbers (similar to Python's range)
(defun iota (count &key (start 0) (step 1))
  (loop for i from start below (+ start (* count step)) by step collect i))

(in-package :cl-user)

; sum-of-factorial-digits calculates the sum of all digits in the factorial of a given number n.
; It first computes the factorial of n, then converts it to a string to process each digit,
; converts each digit back to an integer, and sums them up.
(defun sum-of-factorial-digits (n)
  (let* ((factorial (factorial n))
         (digits (map 'list #'digit-char-p (prin1-to-string factorial))))
    (apply #'+ digits)))

; factorial computes the factorial of a non-negative integer n.
; It uses a recursive approach with tail recursion optimization.
(defun factorial (n)
  (labels ((fact-iter (n acc)
             (if (<= n 1)
                 acc
                 (fact-iter (1- n) (* n acc)))))
    (fact-iter n 1)))

(defun sum-of-factorial-digits (n)
  (let* ((factorial (factorial n))

    (apply #'+ digits)))

; factorial computes the factorial of a non-negative integer n.
; It uses a recursive approach with tail recursion optimization.
(defun factorial (n)
  (labels ((fact-iter (n acc)
             (if (<= n 1)
                 acc
                 (fact-iter (1- n) (* n acc)))))
    (fact-iter n 1)))

(in-package :cl-user)

;; circular-array-rotation performs a circular rotation on an array and returns the elements at specified query positions.
;; Parameters:
;;   arr - the input list of integers to be rotated
;;   k   - the number of positions to rotate the array (right rotation)
;;   queries - a list of indices to query after rotation
;; Returns:
;;   A list of elements from the rotated array at the specified query positions
(defun circular-array-rotation (arr k queries)
  (let* ((n (length arr))
         (k (mod k n)) ; Avoid unnecessary full rotations
         (rotated-array (append (subseq arr (- n k)) (subseq arr 0 (- n k)))))
    (mapcar (lambda (q) (nth q rotated-array)) queries)))

(in-package :cl-user)

; update-inventory updates the current inventory of books based on a list of transactions.
; current-inventory is an association list (alist) where each element is a cons cell (title . quantity).
; transactions is a list of cons cells (title . change), where change can be positive or negative.
; The function modifies the current-inventory alist in place and removes any entries with quantity <= 0.
(defun update-inventory (current-inventory transactions)
  (dolist (transaction transactions)
    (let* ((title (car transaction))
           (change (cdr transaction))
           (existing-entry (assoc title current-inventory)))
      (if existing-entry
          (progn
            (incf (cdr existing-entry) change)
            (when (<= (cdr existing-entry) 0)
              (setf current-inventory (remove existing-entry current-inventory))))
          (when (> change 0)
            (push (cons title change) current-inventory)))))
  current-inventory)

(defpackage :tree-query-processor
  (:use :cl)
  (:export :process-queries))

(in-package :tree-query-processor)

(defun process-queries (n q values edges queries)
  (let ((graph (make-hash-table))  ; adjacency list for the tree
        (subtree-values (make-hash-table)))  ; stores sorted subtree values

    ; Build the adjacency list from edges
    (dolist (edge edges)
      (let ((u (first edge))
            (v (second edge)))
        (push v (gethash u graph '()))
        (push u (gethash v graph '()))))

    ; DFS to collect and sort subtree values
    (labels ((dfs (node parent)
               (let ((subtree-nodes (list (nth (1- node) values))))  ; 1-indexed to 0-indexed
                 (dolist (neighbor (gethash node graph '()))
                   (unless (eql neighbor parent)
                     (setf subtree-nodes (nconc subtree-nodes (dfs neighbor node)))))
                 (setf (gethash node subtree-values)
                       (sort subtree-nodes #'>))  ; sort in descending order
                 subtree-nodes)))
      (dfs 1 nil))  ; start DFS from root node 1

    ; Process each query
    (mapcar (lambda (query)
              (let* ((v (first query))
                     (k (second query))
                     (subtree-val-list (gethash v subtree-values)))
                (count-if (lambda (val) (>= val k)) subtree-val-list)))
            queries)))

(in-package :cl-user)

; split-string splits the input string s into a list of substrings based on given delimiters.
; If the delimiters string is empty, it returns the entire string as one element in the list.
; The function processes each character in the input string, checking if it is a delimiter.
; Non-delimiter characters are accumulated into the current word until a delimiter is encountered,
; at which point the current word is added to the result list.
(defun split-string (s delimiters)
  (if (string= delimiters "")
      (list s)
      (let ((result '())
            (current-word (make-array 0 :element-type 'character :adjustable t :fill-pointer 0))
            (delimiters-set (coerce delimiters 'list)))
        (loop for char across s
              do (if (member char delimiters-set :test #'char=)
                     (when (> (length current-word) 0)
                       (push (copy-seq current-word) result)
                       (setf (fill-pointer current-word) 0))
                     (vector-push-extend char current-word)))
        (when (> (length current-word) 0)
          (push (copy-seq current-word) result))
        (nreverse result))))

(defpackage :next-bigger-number
  (:use :cl)
  (:export :next-bigger))

(in-package :next-bigger-number)

(defun next-bigger (num)
  (let* ((digits (map 'list #'digit-char-p (prin1-to-string num)))
         (length (length digits))
         (i (- length 2)))
    ; Step 1: Find the first digit from the right that is smaller than the next digit
    (loop while (and (>= i 0) (>= (nth i digits) (nth (1+ i) digits)))
          do (decf i))
    ; If no such digit is found, return -1
    (when (= i -1)
      (return-from next-bigger -1))
    ; Step 2: Find the smallest digit on the right side of digits[i] that is larger than digits[i]
    (let ((j (- length 1)))
      (loop while (<= (nth j digits) (nth i digits))
            do (decf j))
      ; Step 3: Swap digits[i] and digits[j]
      (rotatef (nth i digits) (nth j digits))
      ; Step 4: Sort the digits after index i in ascending order
      (setf (cdr (nthcdr i digits)) (sort (cdr (nthcdr i digits)) #'<))
      ; Convert the list of digits back to a number
      (parse-integer (map 'string #'(lambda (d) (code-char (+ d 48))) digits)))))

; is-palindrome checks if a given number is a palindrome.
; A number is a palindrome if it reads the same forwards and backwards.
; The function converts the number to a string and compares it with its reverse.
(defun is-palindrome (number)
  (let ((num-str (write-to-string number)))
    (string= num-str (reverse num-str))))

; product-palindrome-check checks if the product of integers in each test case is a palindrome.
; Each test case is a list where the first element is ignored (assuming it's a case identifier),
; and the rest are the numbers to be multiplied.
; The function returns a list of "Yes" or "No" strings indicating whether the product is a palindrome.
(defun product-palindrome-check (test-cases)
  (mapcar (lambda (case)
            (let ((product (apply #'* (rest case))))
              (if (is-palindrome product) "Yes" "No")))
          test-cases))

(in-package :cl-user)

;; minimum-trees calculates the minimum number of trees required to ensure that there are at least k paths
;; between any two trees in an m x n grid. If it is impossible, it returns -1.
;; 
;; Parameters:
;;   m - number of rows in the grid
;;   n - number of columns in the grid
;;   k - minimum number of paths required between any two trees
;;
;; Returns:
;;   The minimum number of trees required or -1 if it is impossible.
(defun minimum-trees (m n k)
  (if (or (< m 2) (< n 2) (> k (min m n)))
      -1
      k))

;; almost-sorted-sort sorts a list of numbers where the ith number is at most i positions away
;; from its correct position. It performs a modified bubble sort that only checks nearby elements.
(defun almost-sorted-sort (arr)
  (let ((n (length arr)))
    (dotimes (i n arr)  ; Return the array after processing
      (let ((j (max 0 (- i i))))  ; Position where element arr[i] should start checking from
        (do () ((>= j (min n (+ i i 1))))  ; While j < min(n, i + i + 1)
          (when (> (nth j arr) (nth i arr))
            (rotatef (nth i arr) (nth j arr)))  ; Swap elements
          (incf j))))))

(in-package :cl-user)

; binary-search-extended performs an extended binary search to find the number of occurrences of a query in a sorted array.
; It uses two helper functions, find-left-index and find-right-index, to determine the leftmost and rightmost positions of the query.
; If the query is not found, it returns 0.
(defun binary-search-extended (array query)
  (labels ((find-left-index ()
             (let ((lo 0)
                   (hi (length array)))
               (loop while (< lo hi) do
                 (let ((mid (floor (+ lo hi) 2)))
                   (if (< (aref array mid) query)
                       (setf lo (1+ mid))
                       (setf hi mid))))
               lo))
           (find-right-index ()
             (let ((lo 0)
                   (hi (length array)))
               (loop while (< lo hi) do
                 (let ((mid (floor (+ lo hi) 2)))
                   (if (<= (aref array mid) query)
                       (setf lo (1+ mid))
                       (setf hi mid))))
               lo)))
    (let ((left-index (find-left-index))
          (right-index (find-right-index)))
      (if (or (= left-index (length array))
              (/= (aref array left-index) query))
          0
          (- right-index left-index)))))

(in-package :cl-user)

;;; A network path representation with nodes and connections between them.
;;; The connections are bidirectional with associated latencies.

(defstruct network-path
  (nodes (make-hash-table :test 'equal)) ; Set of nodes
  (connections (make-hash-table :test 'equal))) ; Connections between nodes

;;; add-node adds a new node to the network.
;;; Raises an error if the node already exists.
(defun add-node (network node)
  (when (gethash node (network-path-nodes network))
    (error "Node ~a already exists." node))
  (setf (gethash node (network-path-nodes network)) t)
  (setf (gethash node (network-path-connections network)) (make-hash-table :test 'equal)))

;;; connect-nodes connects two nodes with a given latency.
;;; Raises an error if either node doesn't exist or if latency is not positive.
(defun connect-nodes (network node1 node2 latency)
  (validate-network network node1 node2)
  (when (<= latency 0)
    (error "Latency must be a positive number."))
  (setf (gethash node2 (gethash node1 (network-path-connections network))) latency)
  (setf (gethash node1 (gethash node2 (network-path-connections network))) latency))

;;; calculate-latency computes the total latency along a given path.
;;; Raises an error if the path is invalid or if nodes are not directly connected.
(defun calculate-latency (network path)
  (let ((total-latency 0.0))
    (loop for i from 0 below (1- (length path)) do
      (let ((node1 (nth i path))
            (node2 (nth (1+ i) path)))
        (validate-network network node1 node2)
        (unless (gethash node2 (gethash node1 (network-path-connections network)))
          (error "No direct connection between ~a and ~a." node1 node2))
        (incf total-latency (gethash node2 (gethash node1 (network-path-connections network))))))
    total-latency))

;;; validate-network checks if all given nodes exist in the network.
;;; Raises an error if any node doesn't exist.
(defun validate-network (network &rest nodes)
  (dolist (node nodes)
    (unless (gethash node (network-path-nodes network))
      (error "Node ~a does not exist." node))))

(in-package :cl-user)

; pad-vectors pads all vectors to the maximum length among the vectors, replacing 'NIL' values
; with the minimum possible absolute value except zero. If there are no non-zero values,
; use -1 for padding.
; 
; Parameters:
;   vectors - a list of lists (vectors) containing numbers or NILs
;
; Returns:
;   a list of padded vectors with NILs replaced and all vectors of equal length
(defun pad-vectors (vectors)
  (let* ((max-len (apply #'max (mapcar #'length vectors)))
         (non-zero-abs-vals (loop for vec in vectors
                                  for x in vec
                                  when (and x (not (zerop x)))
                                    collect (abs x)))
         (min-abs-val (if non-zero-abs-vals 
                        (apply #'min non-zero-abs-vals) 
                        -1)))
    (mapcar (lambda (vec)
              (let* ((num-pads (- max-len (length vec)))
                     (replaced-vec (mapcar (lambda (x) (if x x min-abs-val)) vec)))
                (append replaced-vec (make-list num-pads :initial-element min-abs-val))))
            vectors)))

; find-triplet-numbers returns a sorted list of integers that appear at least three times in the input list.
; It uses a hash table to count occurrences of each number in the list.
; The function then filters numbers with counts >= 3 and sorts the result.
(defun find-triplet-numbers (lst)
  (let ((count-table (make-hash-table)))
    ; Count occurrences of each number
    (dolist (num lst)
      (incf (gethash num count-table 0)))
    ; Collect numbers with count >= 3
    (let ((result '()))
      (maphash (lambda (num count)
                 (when (>= count 3)
                   (push num result)))
               count-table)
      ; Sort the result
      (sort result #'<))))

; min-largest-split calculates the smallest possible largest substring length when splitting a string s into k parts.
; It uses binary search to efficiently determine the minimal maximum length.
; The function first checks if it's possible to divide the string into k parts with a given maximum length.
(defun min-largest-split (s k)
  (labels ((can-divide (max-length)
             (let ((chunks 1)
                   (current-length 0))
               (loop for char across s do
                 (incf current-length)
                 (when (> current-length max-length)
                   (incf chunks)
                   (setf current-length 1)
                   (when (> chunks k)
                     (return-from can-divide nil))))
               t)))
    (let ((left (max (floor (length s) k) 1))
          (right (length s)))
      (loop while (< left right) do
        (let ((mid (floor (+ left right) 2)))
          (if (can-divide mid)
              (setf right mid)
              (setf left (1+ mid)))))
      left)))

(in-package :cl-user)

; can-complete-routes checks if the given delivery routes can be completed without an infinite loop.
; The function uses depth-first search (DFS) to detect cycles in the directed graph represented by the routes.
; If a cycle is found, it returns NIL, indicating the routes cannot be completed without an infinite loop.
; Otherwise, it returns T, indicating the routes can be completed successfully.
(defun can-complete-routes (routes)
  (let ((graph (make-hash-table :test #'equal))
        (visited (make-hash-table :test #'equal))
        (rec-stack (make-hash-table :test #'equal)))
    
    ; Build the graph as an adjacency list
    (dolist (route routes)
      (let ((start (first route))
            (end (second route)))
        (unless (gethash start graph)
          (setf (gethash start graph) '()))
        (push end (gethash start graph))))
    
    ; Define the DFS function for cycle detection
    (labels ((dfs (node)
               (setf (gethash node visited) t)
               (setf (gethash node rec-stack) t)
               
               (dolist (neighbor (gethash node graph '()))
                 (unless (gethash neighbor visited)
                   (when (dfs neighbor)
                     (return-from dfs t)))
                 (when (gethash neighbor rec-stack)
                   (return-from dfs t)))
               
               (remhash node rec-stack)
               nil))
      
      ; Check each node in the graph for cycles
      (maphash (lambda (node _)
                 (unless (gethash node visited)
                   (when (dfs node)
                     (return-from can-complete-routes nil))))
               graph)
      
      t)))

(defpackage :route-utils-test
  (:use :cl)
  (:export :run-tests))

(in-package :route-utils-test)

(defun can-complete-routes (routes)
  (let ((graph (make-hash-table :test #'equal))
        (visited (make-hash-table :test #'equal))
        (rec-stack (make-hash-table :test #'equal)))
    
    ; Build the graph as an adjacency list
    (dolist (route routes)
      (let ((start (first route))
            (end (second route)))
        (unless (gethash start graph)
          (setf (gethash start graph) '()))
        (push end (gethash start graph))))
    
    ; Define the DFS function for cycle detection
    (labels ((dfs (node)
               (setf (gethash node visited) t)
               (setf (gethash node rec-stack) t)
               
               (dolist (neighbor (gethash node graph '()))
                 (unless (gethash neighbor visited)
                   (when (dfs neighbor)
                     (return-from dfs t)))
                 (when (gethash neighbor rec-stack)
                   (return-from dfs t)))
               
               (remhash node rec-stack)
               nil))
      
      ; Check each node in the graph for cycles
      (maphash (lambda (node _)
                 (unless (gethash node visited)
                   (when (dfs node)
                     (return-from can-complete-routes nil))))
               graph)
      
      t)))


(defun run-tests ()
  (let ((test-cases '((((a b) (b c) (c a)) nil)         ; Cycle: a -> b -> c -> a
                      (((a b) (b c) (c d)) t)          ; No cycle
                      (((a b) (b a)) nil)              ; Cycle: a -> b -> a
                      (((a b) (b c) (a c)) t)          ; No cycle
                      (((a b) (b c) (c b)) nil))))     ; Cycle: b -> c -> b
    (dolist (test-case test-cases)
      (let ((routes (first test-case))
            (expected (second test-case)))
        (assert (eq (can-complete-routes routes) expected)
                () "Test failed for routes ~a. Expected ~a but got ~a"
                routes expected (not expected)))))
  (format t "All tests passed!~%"))

(run-tests)

; sum-unique-values calculates the sum of unique values in a list of integers.
; A value is considered unique if it appears exactly once in the list.
; The function uses a hash table to count the frequency of each number.
(defun sum-unique-values (nums)
  (let ((count-table (make-hash-table)))
    ; Count the frequency of each number
    (dolist (num nums)
      (incf (gethash num count-table 0)))
    ; Sum numbers that appear exactly once
    (loop for num being the hash-keys of count-table
          for freq = (gethash num count-table)
          when (= freq 1)
          sum num)))

(in-package :cl-user)

;; tsp-min-cost calculates the minimum possible sum of the distances for the shortest route
;; that visits every destination exactly once and returns to the starting point.
;; 
;; Args:
;; N: integer : Number of destinations
;; distances: list of lists : NxN matrix where (nth i (nth j distances)) is the distance 
;;                            from destination i to destination j.
;;
;; Returns:
;; integer: Minimum route distance
(defun tsp-min-cost (N distances)
  (let ((min-cost most-positive-fixnum))
    (labels ((permute (lst)
               (if (null lst)
                   (list nil)
                   (loop for elem in lst
                         append (mapcar (lambda (p) (cons elem p))
                                       (permute (remove elem lst)))))))
      (dolist (tour (permute (loop for i from 1 below N collect i)) min-cost)
        (let ((current-cost 0)
              (current-position 0))
          (dolist (next-position tour)
            (incf current-cost (nth current-position (nth next-position distances)))
            (setf current-position next-position))
          (incf current-cost (nth current-position (nth 0 distances)))
          (when (< current-cost min-cost)
            (setf min-cost current-cost)))))))

(defpackage :subarray-utils
  (:use :cl)
  (:export :longest-subarray-with-sum))

(in-package :subarray-utils)

(defun longest-subarray-with-sum (arr S)
  (let ((max-length 0)
        (start-index 0)
        (curr-sum 0)
        (sum-dict (make-hash-table)))
    (loop for i from 0 below (length arr) do
      (incf curr-sum (nth i arr))
      (cond
        ((= curr-sum S)
         (when (> (1+ i) max-length)
           (setf max-length (1+ i))
           (setf start-index 0)))
        ((gethash (- curr-sum S) sum-dict)
         (let ((prev-index (gethash (- curr-sum S) sum-dict)))
           (when (> (- i prev-index) max-length)
             (setf max-length (- i prev-index))
             (setf start-index (1+ prev-index))))))
      (unless (gethash curr-sum sum-dict)
        (setf (gethash curr-sum sum-dict) i)))
    (if (zerop max-length)
        '()
        (subseq arr start-index (+ start-index max-length)))))

(in-package :cl-user)

; preprocess takes a string, converts it to lowercase, removes non-alphabetic characters,
; and returns the characters sorted alphabetically.
; This is used as a key for grouping anagrams.
(defun preprocess (word)
  (let* ((lower-word (string-downcase word))
         (cleaned-word (remove-if-not #'alpha-char-p lower-word)))
    (sort (copy-seq cleaned-word) #'char<)))

; find-anagrams takes a list of strings and returns a list of strings that are anagrams of each other.
; Anagrams are grouped by their preprocessed keys (sorted lowercase letters).
; Only groups with more than one word are included in the result.
(defun find-anagrams (words)
  (let ((anagram-groups (make-hash-table :test 'equal)))
    (dolist (word words)
      (let ((key (preprocess word)))
        (push word (gethash key anagram-groups))))
    (let ((result '()))
      (maphash (lambda (key group)
                 (declare (ignore key))
                 (when (> (length group) 1)
                   (setf result (append result group))))
               anagram-groups)
      result)))

;;; This function generates all permutations of a list.
;;; It is used to generate all possible paths for the traveling salesman problem.
(defun permutations (lst)
  (if (null lst)
      (list nil)
      (loop for element in lst
            append (mapcar (lambda (perm) (cons element perm))
                          (permutations (remove element lst :count 1))))))

;;; minimum-travel-cost calculates the minimum cost to travel all cities and return to the starting city.
;;; It uses permutations to explore all possible paths and finds the one with the minimum cost.
;;; The first city is assumed to be the starting point (city 0).
;;; The cost matrix is a 2D list where costs[i][j] represents the cost from city i to city j.
(defun minimum-travel-cost (n costs)
  (let ((cities (loop for i from 0 below n collect i))
        (min-cost most-positive-fixnum))
    (dolist (perm (permutations cities))
      (when (eql (first perm) 0) ; Assuming city 0 as the starting point
        (let ((current-cost 0))
          (loop for i from 0 below (1- n)
                do (incf current-cost (nth (nth i perm) (nth (nth (1+ i) perm) costs))))
          (incf current-cost (nth (nth (1- n) perm) (nth (first perm) costs))) ; Return to starting city
          (when (< current-cost min-cost)
            (setf min-cost current-cost)))))
    min-cost))

(in-package :cl-user)

;; max-width-ramp calculates the maximum width of a ramp in a list of numbers.
;; A ramp is defined as a pair of indices (i, j) where i <= j and arr[i] <= arr[j].
;; The width of such a ramp is j - i.
;; The function uses a stack to efficiently find the maximum width ramp.
(defun max-width-ramp (arr)
  (let* ((n (length arr))
         (stack '())
         (max-width 0))
    ;; Build a stack of indices of elements in decreasing order
    (dotimes (i n)
      (when (or (null stack) (> (nth (car stack) arr) (nth i arr)))
        (push i stack)))
    ;; Traverse from the end of the list to find the maximum width ramp
    (loop for j from (1- n) downto 0 do
      (loop while (and stack (<= (nth (car stack) arr) (nth j arr))) do
        (setf max-width (max max-width (- j (pop stack))))))
    max-width))

(defpackage :quadratic-solver
  (:use :cl)
  (:export :solve-quadratic))

(in-package :quadratic-solver)

(defun solve-quadratic (a b c)
  (if (zerop a)
      (if (zerop b)
          (if (zerop c)
              "Infinite solutions"
              "No solution")
          (/ (- c) b))
      (let ((discriminant (- (* b b) (* 4 a c))))
        (cond
          ((> discriminant 0)
           (let ((root1 (/ (+ (- b) (sqrt discriminant)) (* 2 a)))
                 (root2 (/ (- (- b) (sqrt discriminant)) (* 2 a))))
             (values root1 root2)))
          ((zerop discriminant)
           (/ (- b) (* 2 a)))
          (t
           (let ((real-part (/ (- b) (* 2 a)))
                 (imaginary-part (/ (sqrt (- discriminant)) (* 2 a))))
             (complex real-part imaginary-part)))))))

(defpackage :palindrome-utils
  (:use :cl)
  (:export :find-palindrome))

(in-package :palindrome-utils)

(defun find-palindrome (s)
  (let ((n (length s)))
    (if (zerop n)
        ""
        (let ((start 0)
              (max-length 1))
          (loop for i from 1 below n do
            ; Check for even length palindromes
            (let ((low (1- i))
                  (high i))
              (loop while (and (>= low 0) (< high n) (char= (char s low) (char s high)))
                    do (when (> (- high low 1) max-length)
                         (setf start low
                               max-length (- high low 1)))
                    (decf low)
                    (incf high)))
            ; Check for odd length palindromes
            (let ((low (1- i))
                  (high (1+ i)))
              (loop while (and (>= low 0) (< high n) (char= (char s low) (char s high)))
                    do (when (> (- high low 1) max-length)
                         (setf start low
                               max-length (- high low 1)))
                    (decf low)
                    (incf high))))
          (subseq s start (+ start max-length))))))

(defpackage :palindrome-utils
  (:use :cl)
  (:export :lcs :min-insertions))

(in-package :palindrome-utils)

(defun lcs (X Y)
  (let* ((m (length X))
         (n (length Y))
         (L (make-array (list (1+ m) (1+ n)) :initial-element 0)))
    (loop for i from 0 to m do
      (loop for j from 0 to n do
        (cond
          ((or (zerop i) (zerop j)) (setf (aref L i j) 0))
          ((char= (char X (1- i)) (char Y (1- j)))
           (setf (aref L i j) (1+ (aref L (1- i) (1- j)))))
          (t (setf (aref L i j) (max (aref L (1- i) j) (aref L i (1- j))))))))
    (aref L m n)))

(defun min-insertions (s)
  (let* ((rev-s (reverse s))
         (lcs-length (lcs s rev-s)))
    (- (length s) lcs-length)))

(defpackage :palindrome-utils-test
  (:use :cl)

(defun lcs (X Y)
  (let* ((m (length X))
         (n (length Y))
         (L (make-array (list (1+ m) (1+ n)) :initial-element 0)))
    (loop for i from 0 to m do
      (loop for j from 0 to n do
        (cond
          ((or (zerop i) (zerop j)) (setf (aref L i j) 0))
          ((char= (char X (1- i)) (char Y (1- j)))
           (setf (aref L i j) (1+ (aref L (1- i) (1- j)))))
          (t (setf (aref L i j) (max (aref L (1- i) j) (aref L i (1- j))))))))
    (aref L m n)))
(defun min-insertions (s)
  (let* ((rev-s (reverse s))
         (lcs-length (lcs s rev-s)))
    (- (length s) lcs-length)))

(defpackage :max-points-utils
  (:use :cl)
  (:export :max-points))

(in-package :max-points-utils)

;; max-points calculates the maximum possible points a participant can earn by solving problems in an optimal order.
;; The optimal order is determined by solving key problems in the specified order and other problems in any order.
;;
;; Parameters:
;;   n - integer, total number of problems
;;   m - integer, number of key problems
;;   points - list of integers, points for each problem
;;   key-problems - list of integers, 1-based indices of key problems in the specified order
;;
;; Returns:
;;   integer, the maximum possible points
(defun max-points (n m points key-problems)
  (let ((max-points 0)
        (key-index 0)
        ;; Convert 1-based key-problems to 0-based
        (key-problems (mapcar #'1- key-problems)))
    (dotimes (i n max-points)
      (if (and (< key-index m) (= i (nth key-index key-problems)))
          (progn
            (incf max-points (nth i points))
            (incf key-index))
          (incf max-points (nth i points))))))

(in-package :cl-user)

;; generate-matrix generates an n x n matrix filled with random integers between min-value and max-value.
;; It uses Common Lisp's built-in random function to generate the values.
(defun generate-matrix (n min-value max-value)
  (loop repeat n
        collect (loop repeat n
                      collect (+ min-value (random (- max-value min-value -1))))))

;; extract-diagonal extracts the diagonal elements starting at (i, j) in the matrix.
;; The diagonal is extracted by incrementing both row and column indices until they exceed the matrix size.
(defun extract-diagonal (matrix i j)
  (let ((n (length matrix))
        (diagonal '()))
    (loop while (and (< i n) (< j n))
          do (push (nth j (nth i matrix)) diagonal)
             (incf i)
             (incf j))
    (reverse diagonal)))

;; replace-diagonal replaces the diagonal elements starting at (i, j) in the matrix with the sorted values.
;; The values are taken from the sorted list and placed back into the matrix along the diagonal.
(defun replace-diagonal (matrix i j sorted-values)
  (let ((n (length matrix))
        (idx 0))
    (loop while (and (< i n) (< j n))
          do (setf (nth j (nth i matrix)) (nth idx sorted-values))
             (incf i)
             (incf j)
             (incf idx)))
  matrix)

;; sort-diagonal sorts the diagonal starting at (i, j) in the matrix.
;; It extracts the diagonal, sorts it, and then replaces it back into the matrix.
(defun sort-diagonal (matrix i j)
  (let* ((diagonal (extract-diagonal matrix i j))
         (sorted-diagonal (sort diagonal #'<)))
    (replace-diagonal matrix i j sorted-diagonal)))

;; generate-and-sort-matrix generates an n x n matrix with random integers between min-value and max-value,
;; and then sorts each diagonal in non-decreasing order.
;; It first generates the matrix, then sorts diagonals starting from the first row and first column.
(defun generate-and-sort-matrix (n min-value max-value)
  (let ((matrix (generate-matrix n min-value max-value)))
    ;; Sort diagonals starting from each element in the first row
    (loop for j from 0 below n
          do (sort-diagonal matrix 0 j))
    ;; Sort diagonals starting from each element in the first column (excluding [0,0])
    (loop for i from 1 below n
          do (sort-diagonal matrix i 0))
    matrix))

(defpackage :platform-calculator
  (:use :cl)
  (:export :convert-time-to-minutes :find-minimum-platforms))

(in-package :platform-calculator)

(defun convert-time-to-minutes (time)
  (let* ((colon-pos (position #\: time))
         (hours (parse-integer (subseq time 0 colon-pos)))
         (minutes (parse-integer (subseq time (1+ colon-pos)))))
    (+ (* hours 60) minutes)))

(defun find-minimum-platforms (arrivals departures)
  (let* ((n (length arrivals))
         (arrival-times (sort (mapcar #'convert-time-to-minutes arrivals) #'<))
         (departure-times (sort (mapcar #'convert-time-to-minutes departures) #'<))
         (platform-needed 0)
         (max-platforms 0)
         (i 0)
         (j 0))
    (loop while (and (< i n) (< j n)) do
      (if (<= (nth i arrival-times) (nth j departure-times))
          (progn
            (incf platform-needed)
            (setf max-platforms (max max-platforms platform-needed))
            (incf i))
          (progn
            (decf platform-needed)
            (incf j))))
    max-platforms))

(in-package :cl-user)

; find-package-weights determines if it's possible to create a set of package weights
; such that each truck's capacity can be exactly matched by a sum of these weights.
; The weights are powers of 2, and the number of weights needed is the ceiling of log2(max_capacity + 1).
; If the input list is empty, it returns "IMPOSSIBLE".
; Otherwise, it returns "POSSIBLE", the number of weights, and the list of weights.
(defun find-package-weights (truck-capacities)
  (if (null truck-capacities)
      "IMPOSSIBLE"
      (let* ((max-capacity (apply #'max truck-capacities))
             (num-weights (ceiling (log (+ max-capacity 1) 2)))
             (weights (loop for i from 0 below num-weights
                            collect (expt 2 i))))
        (values "POSSIBLE" num-weights weights))))

             (weights (loop for i from 0 below num-weights

; min-tasks-for-badges calculates the minimum number of tasks required to collect the specified number of Gold, Silver, and Bronze badges.
; The calculation is based on the following rules:
; - Each Gold badge requires 100 tasks.
; - Each Silver badge requires 50 tasks.
; - Each Bronze badge requires 20 tasks.

; Parameters:
; gold - Number of Gold badges required.
; silver - Number of Silver badges required.
; bronze - Number of Bronze badges required.
; Returns:
; The minimum number of tasks required as an integer.
(defun min-tasks-for-badges (gold silver bronze)
  (let ((tasks-for-gold (* gold 100))
        (tasks-for-silver (* silver 50))
        (tasks-for-bronze (* bronze 20)))
    (max tasks-for-gold tasks-for-silver tasks-for-bronze)))

(in-package :cl-user)

; does-drone-visit determines if the drone visits specified positions based on a series of commands.
; The drone starts at (0, 0) and moves according to the commands ('U', 'D', 'L', 'R').
; It tracks all positions visited during the movement.
; For each query (a position), it checks if the position was visited.
; Returns a list of booleans indicating whether each query position was visited.
(defun does-drone-visit (n commands queries)
  (let ((x 0)
        (y 0)
        (visited-positions (make-hash-table :test 'equal)))
    ; Mark the initial position as visited
    (setf (gethash (list x y) visited-positions) t)
    ; Process each command to update the drone's position
    (loop for command across commands do
      (cond
        ((char= command #\U) (incf y))
        ((char= command #\D) (decf y))
        ((char= command #\L) (decf x))
        ((char= command #\R) (incf x)))
      ; Mark the new position as visited
      (setf (gethash (list x y) visited-positions) t))
    ; Check each query against the visited positions
    (mapcar (lambda (query) (gethash query visited-positions)) queries)))

(in-package :cl-user)

; unique-permutations generates all unique permutations of a string of length k in lexicographical order.
; It first generates all possible permutations, removes duplicates, sorts them, and returns the result.
; 
; Args:
; s (string): The input string.
; k (integer): The length of each permutation.
;
; Returns:
; A sorted list of all unique permutations of length k in lexicographical order.
(defun unique-permutations (s k)
  (let* ((chars (coerce s 'list))
         (perms (permutations chars k))
         (unique-perms (remove-duplicates perms :test #'equal))
         (string-perms (mapcar (lambda (p) (coerce p 'string)) unique-perms)))
    (sort string-perms #'string<)))

; Helper function to generate all permutations of a list of length k.
; This is a recursive implementation that builds permutations step by step.
;
; Args:
; lst (list): The list of elements to permute.
; k (integer): The length of each permutation.
;
; Returns:
; A list of all permutations of lst of length k.
(defun permutations (lst k)
  (if (zerop k)
      '(())
      (loop for elem in lst
            append (mapcar (lambda (p) (cons elem p))
                          (permutations (remove elem lst :count 1) (1- k))))))

(defpackage :grid-utils
  (:use :cl)
  (:export :generate-final-grid))

(in-package :grid-utils)

;; generate-final-grid creates an N x N grid initialized with 'W' characters,
;; then applies operations to modify specific cells based on the input.
;; Each operation is a tuple (X Y C) where:
;; - X and Y are 1-based coordinates
;; - C determines the cell value (1 becomes 'B', anything else becomes 'W')
;; Returns the grid as a list of strings.
(defun generate-final-grid (n m operations)
  (let ((grid (make-array (list n n) :initial-element #\W)))
    (dolist (op operations)
      (destructuring-bind (x y c) op
        (setf (aref grid (1- x) (1- y)) (if (= c 1) #\B #\W))))
    (loop for i below n collect
         (coerce (loop for j below n collect (aref grid i j)) 'string))))

(defpackage :isbn-utils
  (:use :cl)
  (:export :valid-isbn10))

(in-package :isbn-utils)

(defun valid-isbn10 (isbn)
  "Determines if the given string is a valid ISBN-10.
   Returns T if valid, NIL otherwise."
  (unless (= (length isbn) 10)
    (return-from valid-isbn10 nil))
  
  (let ((total 0))
    (dotimes (i 10)
      (let ((char (char isbn i)))
        (cond
          ((char= char #\X)
           (if (= i 9)
               (incf total (* 10 (- 10 i)))
               (return-from valid-isbn10 nil)))
          ((digit-char-p char)
           (incf total (* (digit-char-p char) (- 10 i))))
          (t (return-from valid-isbn10 nil)))))
    (zerop (mod total 11))))

(in-package :cl-user)

; min-moves-to-equal-sticks calculates the minimum number of moves required to make all sticks equal in length.
; The optimal length to adjust all sticks to is the median of the sorted list.
; The function sorts the input list, finds the median, and sums the absolute differences between each stick's length and the median.
; If the input list is empty, it returns 0.
(defun min-moves-to-equal-sticks (sticks)
  (if (null sticks)
      0
      (let* ((sorted-sticks (sort (copy-list sticks) #'<))
             (median (nth (floor (length sorted-sticks) 2) sorted-sticks))
             (total-moves (reduce #'+ (mapcar (lambda (x) (abs (- x median))) sorted-sticks))))
        total-moves)))

(in-package :cl-user)

; is-perfect-square recursively checks if a number n is a perfect square.
; It starts checking from the 'start' value (defaults to 1) and increments until it finds a match or exceeds n.
; 
; Parameters:
; n - The number to check.
; start - The current number to test from (defaults to 1).
;
; Returns:
; t if n is a perfect square, nil otherwise.
(defun is-perfect-square (n &optional (start 1))
  (cond
    ((< n 0) nil) ; Negative numbers cannot be perfect squares
    ((or (= n 0) (= n 1)) t) ; 0 and 1 are perfect squares
    (t (let ((current-square (* start start)))
         (cond
           ((> current-square n) nil) ; Exceeded n without finding a perfect square
           ((= current-square n) t) ; Found a perfect square
           (t (is-perfect-square n (1+ start)))))))) ; Recur with next integer

(in-package :cl-user)

;;; Dijkstra's algorithm implementation in Common Lisp

;;; A priority queue implementation using a list and sorting
(defun priority-queue-push (queue item)
  "Push an item into the priority queue and maintain order."
  (merge 'list (list item) queue #'< :key #'car))

(defun priority-queue-pop (queue)
  "Pop the smallest item from the priority queue."
  (values (car queue) (cdr queue)))

;;; dijkstra calculates the shortest paths from the start node to all other nodes in the graph.
;;; graph is an association list where each node maps to a list of (neighbor . weight) pairs.
;;; start is the starting node.
;;; Returns an association list of (node . distance) pairs.
(defun dijkstra (graph start)
  (let ((priority-queue (list (cons 0 start)))
        (distances (loop for (node) in graph collect (cons node most-positive-fixnum) into dists
                         finally (return (progn (setf (cdr (assoc start dists)) 0) dists)))))
    (loop while priority-queue
          do (multiple-value-bind (current-item remaining-queue) (priority-queue-pop priority-queue)
               (setf priority-queue remaining-queue)
               (let ((current-distance (car current-item))
                     (current-node (cdr current-item)))
                 (when (<= current-distance (cdr (assoc current-node distances)))
                   (dolist (edge (cdr (assoc current-node graph)))
                     (let* ((neighbor (car edge))
                            (weight (cdr edge))
                            (distance (+ current-distance weight))
                            (neighbor-distance (cdr (assoc neighbor distances))))
                       (when (< distance neighbor-distance)
                         (setf (cdr (assoc neighbor distances)) distance)
                         (setf priority-queue (priority-queue-push priority-queue (cons distance neighbor))))))))))
    distances))

(in-package :cl-user)

;; minimum-delivery-cost calculates the minimum total cost required for trucks to deliver packages to all cities
;; from the depot and back. The depot is assumed to be city 0.
;; The cost is calculated as the sum of 2 * cost from depot to each city (round trip).
;;
;; Parameters:
;; - n: integer, number of cities including the depot
;; - cost-matrix: list of lists, n x n matrix where (nth i (nth j cost-matrix)) is the cost from city i to city j
;;
;; Returns:
;; - integer, minimum total cost for the trucks to deliver packages to every city
(defun minimum-delivery-cost (n cost-matrix)
  (let ((total-cost 0))
    ;; Iterate over all cities excluding the depot (city 0)
    (loop for i from 1 below n
          do (incf total-cost (* 2 (nth i (first cost-matrix)))))
    total-cost))

(defpackage :bit-manipulation
  (:use :cl)
  (:export :get-bit :set-bit :clear-bit :update-bit :bit-manipulations))

(in-package :bit-manipulation)

;; get-bit returns the value (0 or 1) of the i-th bit in number n
(defun get-bit (n i)
  (logand (ash n (- i)) 1))

;; set-bit sets the i-th bit in number n to 1 and returns the result
(defun set-bit (n i)
  (logior n (ash 1 i)))

;; clear-bit clears the i-th bit in number n (sets to 0) and returns the result
(defun clear-bit (n i)
  (logand n (lognot (ash 1 i))))

;; update-bit updates the i-th bit in number n to the specified value (0 or 1)
(defun update-bit (n i bit)
  (logior (logand n (lognot (ash 1 i))) (ash bit i)))

;; bit-manipulations performs a series of bit operations on a number
;; operations is a list where each element is either:
;; ('get i) - gets the i-th bit
;; ('set i) - sets the i-th bit
;; ('clear i) - clears the i-th bit
;; ('update i bit) - updates the i-th bit to specified value
;; Returns either a list of get results or the final number
(defun bit-manipulations (num operations)
  (let ((current-num num)
        (result '()))
    (dolist (op operations)
      (case (car op)
        ('get (push (get-bit current-num (cadr op)) result))
        ('set (setf current-num (set-bit current-num (cadr op))))
        ('clear (setf current-num (clear-bit current-num (cadr op))))
        ('update (setf current-num (update-bit current-num (cadr op) (caddr op))))))
    (if (some (lambda (op) (eq (car op) 'get)) operations)
        (reverse result)  ; reverse to maintain order since we used push
        current-num)))

(defpackage :bit-manipulation-test
  (:use :cl)
  (:export :run-tests))

(in-package :bit-manipulation-test)

(defun get-bit (n i)
  (logand (ash n (- i)) 1))

;; set-bit sets the i-th bit in number n to 1 and returns the result
(defun set-bit (n i)
  (logior n (ash 1 i)))

;; clear-bit clears the i-th bit in number n (sets to 0) and returns the result
(defun clear-bit (n i)
  (logand n (lognot (ash 1 i))))

;; update-bit updates the i-th bit in number n to the specified value (0 or 1)
(defun update-bit (n i bit)
  (logior (logand n (lognot (ash 1 i))) (ash bit i)))

;; bit-manipulations performs a series of bit operations on a number
;; operations is a list where each element is either:
;; ('get i) - gets the i-th bit
;; ('set i) - sets the i-th bit
;; ('clear i) - clears the i-th bit
;; ('update i bit) - updates the i-th bit to specified value
;; Returns either a list of get results or the final number
(defun bit-manipulations (num operations)
  (let ((current-num num)
        (result '()))
    (dolist (op operations)
      (case (car op)
        ('get (push (get-bit current-num (cadr op)) result))
        ('set (setf current-num (set-bit current-num (cadr op))))
        ('clear (setf current-num (clear-bit current-num (cadr op))))
        ('update (setf current-num (update-bit current-num (cadr op) (caddr op))))))
    (if (some (lambda (op) (eq (car op) 'get)) operations)
        (reverse result)  ; reverse to maintain order since we used push
        current-num)))


(defun run-tests ()
  ;; Test case 1: Getting bits from 5 (101)
  (assert (equal (bit-manipulations 5 '((get 0) (get 1) (get 2))) '(1 0 1))
          () "Test case 1 failed: Getting bits from 5")
  
  ;; Test case 2: Setting bits on 0 and getting results
  (assert (equal (bit-manipulations 0 '((set 1) (set 3) (get 0) (get 1) (get 3))) '(0 1 1))
          () "Test case 2 failed: Setting bits on 0")
  
  ;; Test case 3: Clearing bits from 15 (1111) and getting results
  (assert (equal (bit-manipulations 15 '((clear 0) (clear 2) (get 0) (get 1) (get 2) (get 3))) '(0 1 0 1))
          () "Test case 3 failed: Clearing bits from 15")
  
  ;; Test case 4: Updating bits on 8 (1000) and getting results
  (assert (equal (bit-manipulations 8 '((update 0 1) (update 1 1) (get 0) (get 1) (get 3))) '(1 1 1))
          () "Test case 4 failed: Updating bits on 8")
  
  ;; Test case 5: Mixed operations on 3 (11)
  (assert (= (bit-manipulations 3 '((set 2) (clear 0) (update 1 0))) 4)
          () "Test case 5 failed: Mixed operations on 3")
  
  (format t "All bit manipulation tests passed!~%"))

(run-tests)

;;; sum-of-digits calculates the sum of the digits in a string representation of a number.
;;; It converts each character in the string to a digit and sums them up.
(defun sum-of-digits (s)
  (loop for d across s
        sum (digit-char-p d)))

;;; custom-sort-book-ids sorts a list of book IDs based on three criteria:
;;; 1. The sum of the digits in the ID (ascending)
;;; 2. The length of the ID (ascending)
;;; 3. The ID itself (lexicographical order, ascending)
(defun custom-sort-book-ids (book-ids)
  (sort (copy-list book-ids)
        (lambda (x y)
          (let ((sum-x (sum-of-digits x))
                (sum-y (sum-of-digits y)))
            (cond
              ((< sum-x sum-y) t)
              ((> sum-x sum-y) nil)
              (t (let ((len-x (length x))
                       (len-y (length y)))
                   (cond
                     ((< len-x len-y) t)
                     ((> len-x len-y) nil)
                     (t (string< x y))))))))))

;;; organize-books processes multiple test cases of book IDs and returns a list of sorted book IDs.
;;; Each test case consists of a count N and a list of N book IDs.
;;; The function sorts each list of book IDs using custom-sort-book-ids.
(defun organize-books (test-cases)
  (mapcar (lambda (test-case)
            (let ((n (first test-case))
                  (book-ids (second test-case)))
              (custom-sort-book-ids book-ids)))
          test-cases))

; can-arrange-balloons checks if it's possible to arrange balloons such that no two consecutive 
; balloons have the same color at any segment position.
; Parameters:
;   n - number of balloons
;   balloons - list of balloon color segment strings
; Returns: "YES" if arrangement possible, "NO" otherwise
(defun can-arrange-balloons (n balloons)
  (let ((perms (permutations balloons)))
    (dolist (perm perms "NO")
      (let ((valid t))
        (dotimes (i (1- n) (return-from can-arrange-balloons "YES"))
          (dotimes (j (length (first balloons)))
            (when (char= (char (nth i perm) j) (char (nth (1+ i) perm) j))
              (setf valid nil)
              (return)))
          (unless valid (return)))))))

; Helper function to generate all permutations of a list
(defun permutations (lst)
  (if (null lst)
      (list nil)
      (mapcan (lambda (x)
                (mapcar (lambda (y) (cons x y))
                        (permutations (remove x lst :count 1))))
              lst)))

; remove-elements returns a new list with every second element removed.
; If the length of the original list is odd, the middle element is also removed.
; The function uses Common Lisp's loop construct to filter elements and handle the middle element removal.
(defun remove-elements (lst)
  (let* ((filtered-list (loop for element in lst
                              for i from 0
                              when (evenp i)
                              collect element))
         (filtered-length (length filtered-list))
         (original-length (length lst)))
    (if (oddp original-length)
        (let ((middle-pos (floor filtered-length 2)))
          (append (subseq filtered-list 0 middle-pos)
                  (subseq filtered-list (1+ middle-pos))))
        filtered-list)))

;;; kth-smallest-pair-distance calculates the kth smallest pair distance in a list of numbers.
;;; The function first sorts the input list, then computes all possible pair distances,
;;; sorts these distances, and finally returns the kth smallest one (1-based index).
;;; 
;;; Parameters:
;;;   arr - a list of numbers
;;;   k - an integer representing the 1-based index of the desired smallest distance
;;;
;;; Returns:
;;;   The kth smallest pair distance as a number
(defun kth-smallest-pair-distance (arr k)
  (let* ((sorted-arr (sort (copy-list arr) #'<))
         (n (length sorted-arr))
         (pair-distances '()))
    (dotimes (i n)
      (do ((j (1+ i) (1+ j)))
          ((>= j n))
        (push (abs (- (nth i sorted-arr) (nth j sorted-arr))) pair-distances)))
    (nth (1- k) (sort pair-distances #'<))))

(defun kth-smallest-pair-distance (arr k)
  (let* ((sorted-arr (sort (copy-list arr) #'<))
         (n (length sorted-arr))

(defun min-additional-connections (n connections)
  (let ((graph (make-hash-table))
        (visited (make-hash-table))
        (components 0))
    
    ; Build the adjacency list
    (dolist (conn connections)
      (let ((a (car conn))
            (b (cadr conn)))
        (push b (gethash a graph '()))
        (push a (gethash b graph '()))))
    
    ; Define a local DFS function
    (labels ((dfs (node)
               (let ((stack (list node)))
                 (loop while stack do
                   (let ((curr (pop stack)))
                     (dolist (neighbor (gethash curr graph '()))
                       (unless (gethash neighbor visited)
                         (setf (gethash neighbor visited) t)
                         (push neighbor stack))))))))
      
      ; Iterate over all nodes to find connected components
      (loop for node from 1 to n do
        (unless (gethash node visited)
          (setf (gethash node visited) t)
          (dfs node)
          (incf components)))
      
      ; The result is the number of components minus one
      (1- components))))

; has-all-unique-chars checks if a string contains all unique characters.
; The check is case insensitive and ignores spaces.
; It returns T if all characters are unique, NIL otherwise.
(defun has-all-unique-chars (s)
  (let* ((clean-str (remove #\Space (string-downcase s)))
         (len (length clean-str)))
    (loop for i from 0 below len
          do (loop for j from (1+ i) below len
                   when (char= (char clean-str i) (char clean-str j))
                   do (return-from has-all-unique-chars nil)))
    t))

;; lexicographically-smallest-string finds the smallest string in a list of strings,
;; considering both the original string and its reverse for each string.
;; The function takes a list of test cases, where each test case is a cons cell (n . strings),
;; with n being the number of strings and strings being the list of strings.
;; It returns a list of the smallest strings for each test case.
(defun lexicographically-smallest-string (test-cases)
  (mapcar 
    (lambda (case)
      (let* ((strings (cdr case))
             (min-string (reduce 
                          (lambda (a b) 
                            (let ((a-min (if (string< a (reverse a)) a (reverse a)))
                                  (b-min (if (string< b (reverse b)) b (reverse b))))
                              (if (string< a-min b-min) a-min b-min)))
                          strings
                          :initial-value (car strings))))
        min-string))
    test-cases))

(in-package :cl-user)

;;; get-distance-to-nearest-mineral calculates the Manhattan distance from the cell (r, c) 
;;; to the nearest cell with a mineral deposit (which contains 1).
;;; grid: a 2D list representing the grid
;;; n: number of rows in the grid
;;; m: number of columns in the grid
;;; r: current row position
;;; c: current column position
;;; Returns the minimum Manhattan distance to the nearest mineral deposit.
(defun get-distance-to-nearest-mineral (grid n m r c)
  (let ((min-distance most-positive-fixnum))
    (dotimes (i n min-distance)
      (dotimes (j m)
        (when (= (nth j (nth i grid)) 1)
          (let ((distance (+ (abs (- r i)) (abs (- c j)))))
            (when (< distance min-distance)
              (setf min-distance distance))))))))

;;; process-queries processes a list of queries on the grid.
;;; n: number of rows in the grid
;;; m: number of columns in the grid
;;; grid: a 2D list representing the grid
;;; queries: a list of queries where each query is either (1 row col) for movement or (2) for distance calculation
;;; Returns a list of distances calculated for type 2 queries.
(defun process-queries (n m grid queries)
  (let ((results '())
        (current-position '(0 0)))
    (dolist (query queries (reverse results))
      (if (= (first query) 1)
          (setf current-position (list (second query) (third query)))
          (let ((distance (get-distance-to-nearest-mineral grid n m (first current-position) (second current-position))))
            (push distance results))))))

(defpackage :product-utils
  (:use :cl)
  (:export :product-except-self))

(in-package :product-utils)

(defun product-except-self (nums)
  (let ((length (length nums)))
    (if (zerop length)
        '()
        (let ((result (make-list length :initial-element 1)))
          ;; Calculate prefix products
          (let ((prefix-product 1))
            (dotimes (i length)
              (setf (nth i result) prefix-product)
              (setf prefix-product (* prefix-product (nth i nums)))))
          ;; Calculate suffix products and multiply with prefix products
          (let ((suffix-product 1))
            (loop for i from (1- length) downto 0 do
              (setf (nth i result) (* (nth i result) suffix-product))
              (setf suffix-product (* suffix-product (nth i nums)))))
          result))))

          (let ((suffix-product 1))
            (loop for i from (1- length) downto 0 do
              (setf (nth i result) (* (nth i result) suffix-product))
              (setf suffix-product (* suffix-product (nth i nums)))))
          result))))

;; choose-k-integers determines if it's possible to choose k integers from the array such that 
;; their sum is greater than or equal to m. If possible, it returns the chosen k integers; 
;; otherwise, it returns -1.
;; The function first sorts the array in descending order and then selects the first k elements.

(defun choose-k-integers (n k m arr)
  (let* ((sorted-arr (sort (copy-list arr) #'>))
         (chosen (subseq sorted-arr 0 k))
         (sum (apply #'+ chosen)))
    (if (>= sum m)
        chosen
        -1)))

; is-prime-p checks if a given number is a prime.
; It returns T if the number is prime, NIL otherwise.
; The function uses trial division optimized for primes greater than 3.
(defun is-prime-p (num)
  (cond
    ((<= num 1) nil)
    ((<= num 3) t)
    ((or (zerop (mod num 2)) (zerop (mod num 3))) nil)
    (t (loop for i from 5 to (isqrt num) by 6
             when (or (zerop (mod num i))
                      (zerop (mod num (+ i 2))))
             return nil
             finally (return t)))))

; prime-pairs-sequence generates a list of n pairs of consecutive prime numbers that are exactly 2 apart (twin primes).
; It returns a list of cons cells (pairs) where each pair consists of two primes (p, p+2).
(defun prime-pairs-sequence (n)
  (let ((primes '())
        (prime-pairs '())
        (current 2)) ; start from the smallest prime number
    (loop while (< (length prime-pairs) n) do
      (when (is-prime-p current)
        (push current primes)
        (when (>= (length primes) 2)
          (let ((last-prime (first primes))
                (second-last-prime (second primes)))
            (when (= last-prime (+ second-last-prime 2))
              (push (cons second-last-prime last-prime) prime-pairs)))))
      (incf current))
    (reverse prime-pairs)))

;; max-non-overlapping-subarrays finds the maximum number of non-overlapping subarrays 
;; in a list of integers that sum up to a given target.
;; The function uses a set to keep track of sums encountered so far and resets the sum 
;; and the set whenever a valid subarray is found.
;; 
;; Parameters:
;;   arr - A list of integers representing the input array.
;;   target - An integer representing the target sum for subarrays.
;;
;; Returns:
;;   An integer representing the maximum number of non-overlapping subarrays with sum equal to target.
(defun max-non-overlapping-subarrays (arr target)
  (let ((sum-so-far 0)
        (count 0)
        (seen-sums (list 0)))
    (dolist (num arr)
      (setf sum-so-far (+ sum-so-far num))
      (if (member (- sum-so-far target) seen-sums :test #'=)
          (progn
            (incf count)
            (setf sum-so-far 0)
            (setf seen-sums (list 0)))
          (push sum-so-far seen-sums)))
    count))
