;;; longest-increasing-sequence calculates the longest strictly increasing subsequence 
;;; of timestamps for each test case using dynamic programming.
;;; 
;;; Parameters:
;;;   t - number of test cases
;;;   test-cases - a list of test cases, where each test case is a list (n timestamps)
;;;                where n is the number of photos and timestamps is a list of numbers
;;;
;;; Returns:
;;;   A list of integers representing the length of the longest increasing sequence for each test case.
(defun longest-increasing-sequence (t-cases test-cases)
  (let ((results '()))
    (dotimes (i t-cases results)
      (let* ((current-case (nth i test-cases))
             (n (first current-case))
             (timestamps (second current-case)))
        (if (zerop n)
            (setf results (cons 0 results))
            (let ((dp (make-list n :initial-element 1)))
              (loop for j from 1 below n do
                (loop for k from 0 below j do
                  (when (< (nth k timestamps) (nth j timestamps))
                    (setf (nth j dp) (max (nth j dp) (1+ (nth k dp)))))))
              (setf results (cons (apply #'max dp) results))))))))

(defun test-longest-increasing-sequence ()
  (let ((test-cases '((5 (1 2 3 4 5))       ; Test case 1: strictly increasing
                      (5 (5 4 3 2 1))       ; Test case 2: strictly decreasing

                      (0 nil)               ; Test case 4: no photos

      (assert (= (nth 0 results) 5) () "Test case 1 failed: Expected 5")
      (assert (= (nth 1 results) 1) () "Test case 2 failed: Expected 1")
      (assert (= (nth 2 results) 4) () "Test case 3 failed: Expected 4")
      (assert (= (nth 3 results) 0) () "Test case 4 failed: Expected 0")
      (assert (= (nth 4 results) 1) () "Test case 5 failed: Expected 1")
      (format t "All tests passed!~%"))))

;;; max-aesthetic-appeal calculates the maximum aesthetic appeal achievable within a given budget
;;; by strategically planting plants in a grid. It uses a knapsack-like approach with backtracking.
;;; 
;;; Parameters:
;;;   budget - the total available budget
;;;   n - number of rows in the grid
;;;   m - number of columns in the grid
;;;   plants - list of plant specifications (cost, appeal, locations)
;;;
;;; Returns:
;;;   The maximum aesthetic appeal achievable within the budget

(defun max-aesthetic-appeal (budget n m plants)
  (labels ((knapsack (k current-budget planted great-aesthetic)
             (cond
               ((or (>= k (length plants)) (< current-budget 0)) 0)
               (t
                (let* ((plant (nth k plants))
                       (cost (first plant))
                       (appeal (second plant))
                       (locations (third plant))
                       (max-appeal (knapsack (1+ k) current-budget planted great-aesthetic)))
                  (dolist (loc locations max-appeal)
                    (let ((row (first loc))
                          (col (second loc)))
                      (unless (aref planted row col)
                        (when (>= current-budget cost)
                          (setf (aref planted row col) t)
                          (let ((temp-appeal (+ (knapsack (1+ k) 
                                                         (- current-budget cost) 
                                                         planted 
                                                         (+ great-aesthetic appeal)) 
                                              appeal)))
                            (setf max-appeal (max max-appeal temp-appeal)))
                          (setf (aref planted row col) nil))))))))))
    
    ;; Sort plants by appeal-to-cost ratio in descending order
    (let ((sorted-plants (sort (copy-list plants) 
                              #'> 
                              :key (lambda (x) (/ (second x) (first x))))))
      (knapsack 0 budget (make-array (list n m) :initial-element nil) 0))))

(defpackage :aesthetic-appeal-test
  (:use :cl)
  (:export :run-tests))

(in-package :aesthetic-appeal-test)

(defun max-aesthetic-appeal (budget n m plants)
  (labels ((knapsack (k current-budget planted great-aesthetic)
             (cond
               ((or (>= k (length plants)) (< current-budget 0)) 0)
               (t
                (let* ((plant (nth k plants))
                       (cost (first plant))
                       (appeal (second plant))
                       (locations (third plant))
                       (max-appeal (knapsack (1+ k) current-budget planted great-aesthetic)))
                  (dolist (loc locations max-appeal)
                    (let ((row (first loc))
                          (col (second loc)))
                      (unless (aref planted row col)
                        (when (>= current-budget cost)
                          (setf (aref planted row col) t)
                          (let ((temp-appeal (+ (knapsack (1+ k) 
                                                         (- current-budget cost) 
                                                         planted 
                                                         (+ great-aesthetic appeal)) 
                                              appeal)))
                            (setf max-appeal (max max-appeal temp-appeal)))
                          (setf (aref planted row col) nil))))))))))
    
    ;; Sort plants by appeal-to-cost ratio in descending order
    (let ((sorted-plants (sort (copy-list plants) 
                              #'> 
                              :key (lambda (x) (/ (second x) (first x))))))
      (knapsack 0 budget (make-array (list n m) :initial-element nil) 0))))


(defun run-tests ()
  ;; Test Case 1: Simple case with one plant that fits in budget
  (let ((result1 (max-aesthetic-appeal 10 2 2 '((5 3 ((0 0)))))))
    (assert (= result1 3) () "Test Case 1 failed: Expected 3, got ~a" result1))
  
  ;; Test Case 2: Multiple plants with overlapping locations
  (let ((result2 (max-aesthetic-appeal 15 3 3 '((5 3 ((0 0) (1 1)))
                                               (7 5 ((0 0) (2 2)))
                                               (3 2 ((1 1))))))))
    (assert (= result2 10) () "Test Case 2 failed: Expected 10, got ~a" result2))
  
  ;; Test Case 3: Budget too small for any plant
  (let ((result3 (max-aesthetic-appeal 2 2 2 '((5 3 ((0 0)))
                                              (4 2 ((1 1))))))))
    (assert (= result3 0) () "Test Case 3 failed: Expected 0, got ~a" result3))
  
  (format t "All tests passed!~%"))

(run-tests)

; is-match checks if a string s matches a pattern p, where '?' in p can match any single lowercase letter.
; Returns "YES" if they match, otherwise "NO".
; The match is determined by comparing each character in s and p, with '?' in p matching any character in s.
; The strings must be of the same length to match.
(defun is-match (s p)
  (if (/= (length s) (length p))
      "NO"
      (loop for s-char across s
            for p-char across p
            unless (or (char= p-char #\?) (char= s-char p-char))
            do (return-from is-match "NO")
            finally (return "YES"))))

(in-package :cl-user)

; find-min-difference-indices returns two distinct indices i and j such that the absolute difference 
; between a[i] and a[j] is minimized. If multiple solutions exist, any one is returned.
; 
; Parameters:
;   n - the length of the list a
;   a - a list of numbers
;
; Returns:
;   Two values: the indices i and j with the minimal absolute difference.
(defun find-min-difference-indices (n a)
  (let* ((indexed-a (loop for i from 1 to n 
                          for x in a 
                          collect (cons x i))) ; Create (value . index) pairs
         (sorted-indexed-a (sort (copy-list indexed-a) #'< :key #'car)) ; Sort by value
         (min-diff most-positive-fixnum)
         (min-i -1)
         (min-j -1))
    (loop for k from 0 to (- n 2) ; Iterate through adjacent pairs
          for current = (nth k sorted-indexed-a)
          for next = (nth (1+ k) sorted-indexed-a)
          for diff = (abs (- (car next) (car current)))
          when (< diff min-diff)
            do (setf min-diff diff
                     min-i (cdr current)
                     min-j (cdr next)))
    (values min-i min-j)))

; convert-vowels replaces all vowels in the input string with their respective positions in the alphabet.
; The function maintains the case sensitivity of the original string.
; The vowel positions are as follows:
; a/A -> 1, e/E -> 5, i/I -> 9, o/O -> 15, u/U -> 21
(defun convert-vowels (s)
  (let ((vowel-map '((#\a . "1") (#\A . "1")
                     (#\e . "5") (#\E . "5")
                     (#\i . "9") (#\I . "9")
                     (#\o . "15") (#\O . "15")
                     (#\u . "21") (#\U . "21"))))
    (with-output-to-string (result)
      (loop for char across s
            do (let ((replacement (cdr (assoc char vowel-map :test #'char=))))
                 (if replacement
                     (princ replacement result)
                     (princ char result)))))))

(in-package :cl-user)

; perform-operations processes a string and a list of queries, performing operations on the string.
; The operations include:
; - Type 1: Change a character at a specified position.
; - Type 2: Check if a substring is a palindrome.
; The function returns a list of results for the type 2 queries.
(defun perform-operations (s queries)
  (let ((s (coerce s 'list))  ; Convert the string to a list for mutability
        (results '()))
    (dolist (query queries)
      (case (first query)
        (1  ; Type 1 query: change character at position i to c
         (let ((i (1- (second query)))
               (c (third query)))
           (setf (nth i s) c)))
        (2  ; Type 2 query: check if substring from l to r is a palindrome
         (let* ((l (1- (second query)))
                (r (third query))
                (substring (subseq s l r))
                (reversed-substring (reverse substring)))
           (if (equal substring reversed-substring)
               (push "YES" results)
               (push "NO" results))))))
    (reverse results)))  ; Reverse to maintain the order of results

(in-package :cl-user)

; rotate-array rotates a list counter-clockwise by a specified number of positions.
; If the input list is empty, it returns the empty list.
; For non-empty lists, it handles positions greater than the list length by using modulo arithmetic.
; The rotation is performed by concatenating the sublist from the rotation position to the end 
; with the sublist from the beginning up to the rotation position.
(defun rotate-array (arr positions)
  (if (null arr)
      arr
      (let* ((n (length arr))
             (effective-pos (mod positions n)))
        (append (subseq arr effective-pos) (subseq arr 0 effective-pos)))))

(in-package :cl-user)

; unique-paths calculates the number of unique paths from the top-left corner to the bottom-right corner
; of an x by y grid, moving only right or down. It uses memoization to optimize the recursive solution.
; The function takes two integers x and y, and an optional memoization table (defaults to an empty hash table).
; Returns the number of unique paths as an integer.
(defun unique-paths (x y &optional (memo (make-hash-table :test 'equal)))
  (let ((key (list x y)))
    (when (gethash key memo)
      (return-from unique-paths (gethash key memo)))
    (if (or (= x 1) (= y 1))
        (setf (gethash key memo) 1)
        (setf (gethash key memo) 
              (+ (unique-paths (1- x) y memo) 
                 (unique-paths x (1- y) memo))))))

; check-password-strength checks if given passwords meet the specified criteria for a valid password.
; A valid password must:
; - Be at least 8 characters long
; - Contain at least one lowercase letter
; - Contain at least one uppercase letter
; - Contain at least one digit
; - Contain at least one special character from [!@#$%^&*()\-+]
; The function returns a list of booleans where each element is T if the corresponding password is valid, otherwise NIL.
(defun check-password-strength (passwords)
  (mapcar (lambda (password)
            (and (>= (length password) 8)
                 (some #'lower-case-p password)
                 (some #'upper-case-p password)
                 (some #'digit-char-p password)
                 (some (lambda (c) (find c "!@#$%^&*()-+")) password)))
          passwords))

;; minimize-max-difficulty calculates the minimum possible value of the maximum difficulty Petya will encounter.
;; The function first sorts the list of difficulties and then returns the middle element (or the left-middle for even lengths).
;; This is based on the observation that the optimal solution is the median of the sorted list.
;;
;; Parameters:
;;   n - the number of elements in the difficulties list
;;   difficulties - a list of integers representing the difficulties
;;
;; Returns:
;;   The minimum possible value of the maximum difficulty after optimal arrangement.
(defun minimize-max-difficulty (n difficulties)
  (let ((sorted-difficulties (sort (copy-list difficulties) #'<)))
    (nth (floor (1- n) 2) sorted-difficulties)))

(defpackage :travel-time
  (:use :cl)
  (:export :calculate-travel-time :parse-time))

(in-package :travel-time)

; calculate-travel-time calculates the total travel time in minutes from the first departure
; to the last arrival in a train schedule.
; The schedule is a list of stops, where each stop is represented as a plist with :arrival and :departure keys.
; Times are expected to be in "HH:MM" format as strings.
; Returns the total travel time in minutes as an integer.
(defun calculate-travel-time (schedule)
  (let ((first-departure-time nil)
        (last-arrival-time nil))
    ; Find first departure and last arrival times
    (dolist (stop schedule)
      (when (and (getf stop :departure) (null first-departure-time))
        (setf first-departure-time (getf stop :departure)))
      (when (getf stop :arrival)
        (setf last-arrival-time (getf stop :arrival))))
    
    ; Parse time strings and calculate difference
    (let* ((departure-time (parse-time first-departure-time))
           (arrival-time (parse-time last-arrival-time))
           (time-diff (- arrival-time departure-time)))
      ; Convert seconds to minutes
      (/ time-diff 60))))

; Helper function to parse "HH:MM" time strings into total seconds since midnight
(defun parse-time (time-string)
  (let* ((colon-pos (position #\: time-string))
         (hour (parse-integer (subseq time-string 0 colon-pos)))
         (minute (parse-integer (subseq time-string (1+ colon-pos)))))
    (+ (* hour 3600) (* minute 60))))

(defun find-unique-elements (numbers)
  "Takes a sorted list of integers and returns a new list containing all unique 
   integers from the input list, preserving the original order."
  (if (null numbers)
      '()
      (let ((unique-elements (list (first numbers))))
        (loop for i from 1 below (length numbers)
              do (when (not (equal (nth i numbers) (nth (1- i) numbers)))
                   (setf unique-elements (append unique-elements (list (nth i numbers))))))
        unique-elements)))

(in-package :cl-user)

; length-of-longest-distinct-subarray calculates the length of the longest subarray 
; with all distinct elements in the given list of numbers.
; It uses a sliding window approach with a hash table to keep track of the last seen 
; positions of elements to efficiently update the window boundaries.
(defun length-of-longest-distinct-subarray (nums)
  (let ((n (length nums))
        (max-length 0)
        (left 0)
        (seen (make-hash-table)))
    (if (zerop n)
        0
        (progn
          (loop for right from 0 below n do
            (let ((current (nth right nums)))
              (when (and (gethash current seen) (>= (gethash current seen) left))
                (setf left (1+ (gethash current seen))))
              (setf (gethash current seen) right)
              (setf max-length (max max-length (- right left 1)))))
          max-length))))

(in-package :cl-user)

;; min-time-cost calculates the minimum time cost for each query range of segments.
;; 
;; Parameters:
;; - n: Number of segments (unused in the function but kept for interface consistency)
;; - q: Number of queries (unused in the function but kept for interface consistency)
;; - time-costs: List of time costs for each segment
;; - queries: List of query tuples indicating the range of segments in the form (l r)
;;
;; Returns a list of minimum time costs for each query range.
(defun min-time-cost (n q time-costs queries)
  (mapcar (lambda (query)
            (let ((l (first query))
                  (r (second query)))
              (apply #'min (subseq time-costs (1- l) r))))
          queries))

(in-package :cl-user)

;;; longest-consecutive-sequence calculates the length of the longest consecutive sequence in a grid.
;;; A consecutive sequence is defined as adjacent cells (up, down, left, right) where each subsequent cell's value is 1 greater than the previous.
;;; The function uses depth-first search (DFS) with memoization to optimize repeated calculations.
;;; 
;;; Parameters:
;;;   grid - A 2D list of numbers representing the grid.
;;; Returns:
;;;   The length of the longest consecutive sequence found in the grid.

(defun longest-consecutive-sequence (grid)
  (if (or (null grid) (null (first grid)))
      0
      (let ((memo (make-hash-table :test 'equal)))
        (labels ((dfs (x y)
                   (let ((key (cons x y)))
                     (if (gethash key memo)
                         (gethash key memo)
                         (let ((max-len 1))
                           (dolist (dir '((-1 0) (1 0) (0 -1) (0 1)) max-len)
                             (let* ((dx (first dir))
                                    (dy (second dir))
                                    (nx (+ x dx))
                                    (ny (+ y dy)))
                               (when (and (<= 0 nx (1- (length grid)))
                                          (<= 0 ny (1- (length (first grid))))
                                          (= (aref (make-array (list (length grid) (length (first grid)))
                                                               :initial-contents grid)
                                                  nx ny)
                                             (1+ (aref (make-array (list (length grid) (length (first grid)))
                                                                   :initial-contents grid)
                                                       x y))))
                                 (setf max-len (max max-len (1+ (dfs nx ny)))))))
                           (setf (gethash key memo) max-len))))))
          (loop for x from 0 below (length grid)
                maximize (loop for y from 0 below (length (first grid))
                              maximize (dfs x y)))))))

Longest consecutive sequence: 4

(in-package :cl-user)

; string-reorder reorders the characters in a string according to the given indices.
; It takes a string and a list of indices, then constructs a new string where each character
; from the original string is placed at the corresponding index in the indices list.
; If the indices list is shorter than the string, the behavior is undefined.
(defun string-reorder (s indices)
  (let* ((len (length s))
         (result (make-array len :element-type 'character :initial-element #\Space)))
    (loop for i from 0 below (length indices)
          for index = (nth i indices)
          do (setf (aref result index) (char s i)))
    (coerce result 'string)))

(in-package :cl-user)

; fibonacci generates a list of the first n Fibonacci numbers.
; The Fibonacci sequence starts with 0 and 1, and each subsequent number is the sum of the two preceding ones.
; Args:
;   n - The number of Fibonacci numbers to generate.
; Returns:
;   A list of the first n Fibonacci numbers.
(defun fibonacci (n)
  (let ((a 0)
        (b 1)
        (fib-sequence '()))
    (dotimes (i n fib-sequence)
      (push a fib-sequence)
      (psetf a b
             b (+ a b)))
    (reverse fib-sequence)))

(in-package :cl-user)

; find-mode computes the mode(s) of a given list of numbers.
; The mode is the value that appears most frequently in the dataset.
; If there are multiple values with the same maximum frequency, all are returned.
; The returned modes are sorted in ascending order.
; If the input list is empty, an empty list is returned.
(defun find-mode (data)
  (if (null data)
      '()
      (let* ((frequency-table (make-hash-table))
             (max-frequency 0)
             (modes '()))
        ; Count frequencies of each number in the data
        (dolist (number data)
          (incf (gethash number frequency-table 0)))
        ; Find the maximum frequency
        (maphash (lambda (number freq)
                   (when (> freq max-frequency)
                     (setf max-frequency freq)))
                 frequency-table)
        ; Collect all numbers with max frequency
        (maphash (lambda (number freq)
                   (when (= freq max-frequency)
                     (push number modes)))
                 frequency-table)
        ; Return sorted modes
        (sort modes #'<))))

Input: NIL
